7. This is said in the first place because tne motion of the world proceeds from the rising of the sun to its setting. And it first exists in that quarter from which it is moved;
Genesis ii. 8. 


secondly, because tnat part of the world which is in the region of the east is called the right side; and that which is in the region of the west is called the left side of the world.

But the sacred writer here points out in an enigmatical manner, that wickedness, when it has gone forth out of doors, to the swelling whirlpools of the vices and passions which overflow and corrupt the soul and life, joyfully admits them, and dwells with and takes up its abode with them, as with its nearest friends and relations; but virtue, turning away with loathing from even the first sight of them, at once springs back, and does not return, scarcely finding rest for its feet;
Genesis viii. 9. 


finding, in fact, no standing ground anywhere, and no place worthy of itself. For what other greater evil can there be than this, that virtue should not be able to find in the soul any place ever so small for rest and for abiding in ?
